3. Notes on Exploration Topics


A. Child Process – fork()

A process is an executing instance of a program. In Unix and Linux systems, a new process can be created using the fork() system call.

The fork() function creates a child process that is almost identical to the parent process. After fork() is called, both the parent and child continue execution from the next instruction.

Return Values of fork()
Returns 0 in the child process.
Returns the child's Process ID (PID) in the parent process.
Returns -1 if process creation fails.
Characteristics of fork()
Parent and child execute independently.
Each process has its own memory space.
Variables are copied from the parent to the child.
The child receives a unique Process ID.
Applications
Process creation in operating systems.
Shell command execution.
Server process management.
Parallel computing.
B. Handling Common Signals

Signals are software interrupts used to notify a process that a specific event has occurred.

SIGINT

Generated when the user presses Ctrl + C.

Default action:
Terminate the process.

Typical use:
Interrupting a running program.

SIGTERM

Used to request graceful process termination.

Default action:
Terminate the process.

Typical use:
Stopping applications safely.

SIGKILL

Forces immediate process termination.

Characteristics:

Cannot be caught.
Cannot be ignored.
Cannot be handled.

Typical use:
Terminating unresponsive processes.

SIGSEGV

Generated when a program attempts invalid memory access.

Common causes:

Dereferencing a NULL pointer.
Accessing memory outside array bounds.
Using invalid memory addresses.

Default action:
Program termination with a segmentation fault error.

SIGALRM

Generated when a timer set using alarm() expires.

Typical use:
Timeout management.

C. Exploring Different Kernel Crashes

A kernel crash, commonly known as a kernel panic, occurs when the operating system kernel encounters a critical error from which it cannot recover.

Common Causes
Faulty device drivers.
Corrupted kernel modules.
Invalid memory access in kernel mode.
Hardware failures.
Stack overflow.
Synchronization errors.
Symptoms
System freeze.
Unexpected reboot.
Kernel panic message.
System becoming unresponsive.
Prevention
Use stable device drivers.
Regularly update the operating system.
Perform memory diagnostics.
Validate kernel modules before installation.
Follow proper synchronization practices.
D. Time Complexity

Time complexity measures how the execution time of an algorithm grows with input size.

Common Time Complexities
O(1) – Constant Time

Execution time remains constant regardless of input size.

Example:
Accessing an array element.

O(log n) – Logarithmic Time

Execution time increases slowly as input size grows.

Example:
Binary Search.

O(n) – Linear Time

Execution time increases proportionally with input size.

Example:
Linear Search.

O(n log n)

Commonly seen in efficient sorting algorithms.

Examples:

Merge Sort
Heap Sort
Quick Sort (average case)
O(n²) – Quadratic Time

Execution time grows rapidly with input size.

Example:
Bubble Sort.

O(2ⁿ) – Exponential Time

Execution time doubles with every increase in input size.

Example:
Recursive Fibonacci algorithm.

O(n!)

Extremely expensive complexity.

Example:
Brute-force Traveling Salesman Problem.

Importance of Time Complexity
Predicts algorithm performance.
Helps compare algorithms.
Improves software scalability.
Assists in optimization.
E. Locking Mechanisms – Mutex and Spinlock

In multithreaded programs, multiple threads may try to access shared resources simultaneously. Locking mechanisms are used to prevent race conditions and ensure data consistency.

Mutex (Mutual Exclusion Lock)

A mutex allows only one thread at a time to enter a critical section.

When a thread acquires a mutex, all other threads attempting to acquire the same mutex must wait until it is released.

Advantages of Mutex
Efficient for long waiting periods.
Conserves CPU resources.
Suitable for user-space applications.
Disadvantages of Mutex
Context switching overhead.
Slightly slower for very short critical sections.
Applications
Shared counters.
Shared files.
Database access.
Resource management.
Spinlock

A spinlock continuously checks whether a lock is available instead of sleeping.

The waiting thread repeatedly executes a loop until the lock becomes free.

Advantages of Spinlock
No context-switching overhead.
Very fast for short critical sections.
Suitable for kernel-level programming.
Disadvantages of Spinlock
Wastes CPU cycles while waiting.
Not suitable for long waiting periods.
Applications
Operating system kernels.
Device drivers.
Multiprocessor synchronization.
